Rethinking the very American ideal of labor rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have put forward a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota-based Democrat and deputy chairman of Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I am proud to introduce the Employee Empowerment Act together with the Civil Rights Icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities when discriminating for the organization of trade unions as for other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-union forces.
Complementing the National Labour Law Act to provide an opportunity for workers exposed to discrimination to organize a trade union representation, to sue a civil court for justice – and to receive damages or fines – is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it’s certainly not a radical initiative – at least not according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors of their bill suggest is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks that trade unions have faced in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country – Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac encouraged Arthur and his staff to adopt a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their trade unions played a role in the creation of a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that “the workers’ rights to union and joint bargaining and action are guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would make sure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing the fact that the workers would have to organize and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: “The right to establish associations in order to safeguard and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to diminish this right are null and void; measures aimed at them are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the other authors provided a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form or join trade unions for the protection of their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans stated that the right to found a union – and that this union would then be allowed to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies – must be protected.
After these rights have come under fire in America, it is indeed very wise to reconsider the American ideal, whereby the working population must have the right to unite and to be heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
The story is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers’ movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, work miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and we should do that.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and redeemed the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily stops law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to shut down
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday provisionally stopped the implementation of a law in Louisiana that lawyers say would have presumably led to the closure of all five state abortion clinics.
This measure, brought into law by Bobby Jindal, Governor of Louisiana, in June and scheduled to come into force on Sept. 1, would force doctors performing abortions to acquire a patient admission right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to carry out legal abortions for the time being while applying for such a right.
“The plaintiffs can continue to work in accordance with the law as they strive to obtain these rights,” Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within a month, a hearing is set for the judge to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of judgments against similar measures, and said doctors thus gain more time to gain hospital admission rights.
“Today’s decision means women in Louisiana are escaping a sneaky law that wants to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chairman of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the judgment also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the action and had also applied for rights of instruction.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, with courts recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key points of a Texas law that would have forced most of the state’s remaining clinics to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Abortion opponents argue that the measures serve to protect women’s health, although some also welcomed the effects of shutting down clinics.
Only one doctor conducting abortions in Louisiana has patient identification rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the operation for fear of his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the ruling, Louisiana state officials said they would not penalize doctors for conducting abortions while their applications for patient admission rights were still pending.
Delayed diagnoses and lack of access to the best treatment options lead to higher death rates from ovarian cancer in rural areas.
