Genetic disorder often misdiagnosed
A British woman says she thought she would die as a result of a misdiagnosis over many years.
Karin Rodgers lived almost all of her youth in the belief that she had only a few years left to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
She actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
Charity CMT UK said that misdiagnoses are a common problem in people with CMT because so little is known about this disease.
About 23,000 people in the UK are believed to suffer from CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an unsafe gait and curved toes.
Patients also suffer from numbness or pain. The disease is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she was suffering from Peace Kingdom Ataxia (FA) – a disease with very poor chances of survival.
Rodgers thought she would sit in a wheelchair before she turned 18 and die before her 30th birthday.
The mother of two children, who is now 51 years old, said, “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same as the others.
I fell down all the time and it took me longer.
I could never ride roller skating or skateboarding with the other kids and was often teased at school because of my way of walking and running.
Rodgers said that at the age of 13, after several operations to relieve her Achilles tendon and stretch her feet, she saw her medical records when her doctor had left the room and read that she was suffering from FA.
"I felt guilty because I had been curious, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, looked for the disease in the library, and wrote to the FA Society," she said.
When I received an answer, I was shocked and terribly panicked.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die at 25, and in between would slowly lose all my skills.
I made it all up with myself and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17, she realized that her abilities had not decreased as much as she had imagined and asked her doctor.
He just got up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have that, or you'd be in a wheelchair right now."
I think you have something far less life-threatening.
After some genetic tests, her CMT was detected.
“When he explained to me what CMT was, I felt like I was a winner,” she said.
Charity CMT UK has launched a CMT awareness month to draw attention to this disease.
