Tax burden on businessmen in the Washington area increases with economic recovery
A recovery in the economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax rulings for businesses in the country rose slightly last year as economic recovery accelerated, according to a newly published study last week, and companies in the Washington area were no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia area jointly paid $27.6 billion to government and local agencies in fiscal year 2013, an increase of 3.8 percent compared to revenues of $26.6 billion in 2012.
The state and local tax burden of companies increased by 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, compared to 3.9 percent the year before, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of declining resolutions in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes increased more than local taxes, by 4.3 percent, according to the study conducted by the service agency Ernst & Young with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s revenue comes from companies.
Virginia has the lowest tax revenue from companies at 28%.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is due to a recovery in corporate property values, the researchers say, leading to a 3.7 percent increase in property taxes this year after the three consecutive years with growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While a large part of these profits came from major states such as California, New York and Texas, the process seems to be true for the Washington area as well.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia jointly paid over $10 billion in government and local property taxes last year, compared to $9.6 billion in 2012 – an increase of 4.2 percent over the course of a year.
But the apparent real estate asset recovery isn’t as effective in raising state and local tax revenues in Maryland as real estate taxes amount to just over a fifth of corporate tax receipts.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay almost half of their state and local taxes in the form of property taxes.
“The following is happening in Maryland: a large part of the real estate, especially in the tax area around D.C., is either owned by the government or by nonprofits that don’t pay real estate taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, in order to be able to provide the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed to the recovery of the real estate market alone
Business revenues also seem to be recovering, according to the data.
Companies in the region reported income taxes on government organizations of $2.3 billion compared to 2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland raised $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the highest amount in the region.
While the trend is going in the same direction, the local tax burden for companies does not rise evenly in all three locations.
The rate of increase in the district was 4.3 percent to the national average, while the rise in Maryland was significantly higher, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported a below-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia has the significantly lowest corporate income taxes, with 6 percent in all three departments (all three have fixed corporate tax rates).
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25 percent and in the district is relatively high 9.975 percent.
A comparable study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that lower state and local corporate taxes are required in Virginia, and overall there is a better tax climate than in Maryland.
The study did not examine the district.
Despite the benefits, Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbors.
North Carolina has passed laws to lower its corporate tax rates from 6.9 percent to 6 percent this year, the same rate as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
