Putin asks Kiev to start 'statehood talks' with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin, according to Russian media reports on Sunday, demanded that the Ukrainian government stop fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the “statehood” of the renegade region.
His spokesman, Dimitri Peskov, later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become part of Russia, but that his status towards Ukraine had to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent his rights and interests.
Putin’s call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the outbreak of the riots five months ago: help the separatists capture territories and pressure on the Ukrainian government to enable the newly proclaimed Novorossia region to gain de facto independence for an alliance with Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with the state-owned TV channel Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture the separatist-held territories in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian Crimea peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossia" or "New Russia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary peak of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of Ukrainian politicians’ campaigns for the 26 Oct. elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in the separatist-held areas, hope for soon peace talks “are trapped in their illusions,” Itar-Tass reported.
“We need to immediately record in-depth discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of Southeast Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there,” he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood should be seen in context with the greater autonomy that has been discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, “because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine.”
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarification to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underscores Russia’s leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty in annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and pre-conflict polls showed a broad majority for staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and external relations, thus giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is home to most of the Russian Navy as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that make important components for the Russian military.
In his inauguration speech on 7 June, Ukrainian President Petro Porozhenko proposed that Ukrainian legislation, after new elections, should consider additions to the constitution, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to that of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose armament and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate with the separatist leaders on an equal footing followed last week after a further advance by the rebels after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoazovsk in a sweep, which Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industrial port of 500,000 inhabitants, located between Novoazovsk and the narrow access to Crimea peninsula.
Poroschenko spoke at a meeting of the EU leadership in Brussels on Saturday and urged action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
“We are close to a point where there is no going back,” Poroschenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on concrete actions, the leadership demanded the draft further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaysk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers invaded the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, Colonel Andrij Lysenko, spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defence Council reported Saturday in Kiev.
